1
00:00:00,030 --> 00:00:03,000
***Subtitles by Ardarvin & Mayumi***

2
00:00:03,440 --> 00:00:07,120
Once again, only on TVer, we're showing what happened before the taping

3
00:00:07,140 --> 00:00:10,480
with Hamada and Hirodo doing their pre-show check.

4
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:12,320
Hamada-san, happy New Year.

5
00:00:12,340 --> 00:00:13,560
Happy New Year.

6
00:00:13,580 --> 00:00:16,220
This time as well we'll be streaming on TVer.

7
00:00:16,240 --> 00:00:18,090
So let’s nail it right now.

8
00:00:18,110 --> 00:00:20,420
Yeah, of course we will.

9
00:00:20,450 --> 00:00:24,360
Our first New Year challenge is wine.

10
00:00:24,380 --> 00:00:30,800
The correct one is a top-class wine that goes for 1 million yen a bottle at luxury hotels.

11
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:34,970
They will compare it against a 5,000 yen wine.

12
00:00:34,990 --> 00:00:39,770
By the way, in the main show, seven pairs got it right.

13
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:44,130
Only veteran singer Tendo Yoshimi got it wrong.

14
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:47,880
I really thought I had it right, you know.

15
00:00:48,620 --> 00:00:54,020
Needless to say to this man chose correctly.

16
00:00:54,040 --> 00:00:55,900
We’re still doing wine, huh?

17
00:00:55,920 --> 00:00:56,820
Forever.

18
00:00:56,880 --> 00:01:01,140
People might not have noticed, but the moment the wine came out Hamada-san crossed his legs.

19
00:01:01,160 --> 00:01:02,670
That’s real confidence, Hamada-san.

20
00:01:02,680 --> 00:01:04,580
We've been doing this a while

21
00:01:04,940 --> 00:01:10,330
First up, the correct one: the 1-million-yen wine.

22
00:01:13,770 --> 00:01:16,580
Do you really need to look that close?

23
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:19,160
I look like Okahachiro (old-school Kansai comedian)

24
00:01:27,660 --> 00:01:31,970
Next, B: the 5,000-yen wine.

25
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:43,900
And the answer they chose is...

26
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:46,560
That turned out well.

27
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:51,080
I kind of don’t like that our answers match.

28
00:01:51,220 --> 00:01:53,940
There’s that 'because it’s aged' thing.

29
00:01:53,970 --> 00:01:55,160
How should I put it...

30
00:01:55,280 --> 00:01:57,040
Like, over a long time it’s been...

31
00:01:58,010 --> 00:01:59,590
sitting in the barrel, soaking in

32
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:01,900
'Rested in the barrel' wine.

33
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:02,900
Something like that.

34
00:02:02,930 --> 00:02:06,680
I felt like that kind of aroma just slid right in.

35
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:08,210
What about you?

36
00:02:08,420 --> 00:02:11,170
The smell when they poured it,

37
00:02:11,190 --> 00:02:12,720
it was obviously...

38
00:02:12,740 --> 00:02:16,060
The aroma the moment the wine was poured was overwhelmingly better.

39
00:02:16,090 --> 00:02:19,510
Make sure you count that, okay? How many comments he steals from me.

40
00:02:19,720 --> 00:02:20,140
OK!

41
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:22,260
Let’s make 2026 a really good year.

42
00:02:22,380 --> 00:02:23,020
OK!

43
00:02:23,380 --> 00:02:24,930
The correct answer is

44
00:02:25,020 --> 00:02:26,120
A.

45
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:27,750
Nice.

46
00:02:27,820 --> 00:02:28,840
That’s really good.

47
00:02:30,680 --> 00:02:33,190
2026 is going to be different.

48
00:02:33,620 --> 00:02:35,930
With that correct answer, they stay top-class.

49
00:02:36,040 --> 00:02:39,260
Sounds like 2026 is off to a good start, right?

50
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:42,860
Check 2: Tate sword-fighting.

51
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:53,270
The correct answer is B: an elite tate troupe with over 30 years of experience and more than 20,000 stage slashes.

52
00:02:53,450 --> 00:02:59,910
And the wrong one, A, was a young tate troupe with much less experience.

53
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:03,640
On a question an actor absolutely shouldn’t miss,

54
00:03:03,650 --> 00:03:07,620
Tae Kimura got it wrong.

55
00:03:07,890 --> 00:03:16,660
And proved too difficult for current idols FRUITS ZIPPER and Hey! Say! JUMP.

56
00:03:16,980 --> 00:03:21,340
This segment is presented as a period-drama-style mini story.

57
00:03:21,430 --> 00:03:26,790
The lead, fleeing with the princess from evil pursuers, is played by Ryuji Harada.

58
00:03:32,940 --> 00:03:35,490
Se’s basically a regular on this show now.

59
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:40,520
With that princess, you could just leave her behind, couldn’t you?

60
00:03:40,780 --> 00:03:44,700
Ryuji, I am sorry to always burden you so.

61
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:46,260
Come, let us go.

62
00:03:48,560 --> 00:03:55,330
The evil boss targeting the princess is played by veteran actor Satoshi Jimbo.

63
00:03:57,420 --> 00:04:00,980
Ryuji, your fate is sealed.

64
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,570
First, the wrong answer, A.

65
00:04:29,140 --> 00:04:33,480
 Next up the professionals...

66
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:04,520
As I expected Ryuji

67
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:07,680
But do not think it ends here.

68
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:24,240
He very stubborn

69
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:27,020
What are you even doing?

70
00:05:27,310 --> 00:05:29,270
So annoying

71
00:05:31,490 --> 00:05:33,490
It's too long!

72
00:05:39,030 --> 00:05:41,060
Please die already!

73
00:05:42,880 --> 00:05:44,960
Jinbo-san is taking too long

74
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,280
...so we will skip the ending

75
00:05:49,340 --> 00:05:51,440
Their answer is...

76
00:05:52,770 --> 00:05:54,770
We are matched

77
00:05:55,400 --> 00:05:57,510
Why did you pick B?

78
00:05:58,830 --> 00:06:06,490
They kept making sounds and reacting the whole time,

79
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:08,930
it wasn’t just, 'get cut and fall down.'

80
00:06:09,020 --> 00:06:10,980
In all the other moments too,

81
00:06:11,050 --> 00:06:13,440
the way they stayed in character was impressive.

82
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:15,640
I felt there was a real depth to it.

83
00:06:15,740 --> 00:06:20,200
With B, from the moment they appeared,

84
00:06:21,260 --> 00:06:22,400
how to say...

85
00:06:23,340 --> 00:06:25,470
there was this sense of ease, of being used to it.

86
00:06:25,880 --> 00:06:32,870
Group A came out all hyped up and excited.

87
00:06:33,100 --> 00:06:35,050
Like, 'Let’s do our best!'

88
00:06:35,070 --> 00:06:35,860
You said it.

89
00:06:36,070 --> 00:06:37,360
This is pure Hamada logic.

90
00:06:37,410 --> 00:06:38,840
A just rushed in, 'Bam!'

91
00:06:38,920 --> 00:06:43,130
B wasn’t especially fast, just solid and steady.

92
00:06:43,480 --> 00:06:45,440
But, you know, the thing we can’t tell is,

93
00:06:46,300 --> 00:06:50,950
they might be doing that on purpose, right?

94
00:06:51,100 --> 00:06:53,680
Ok shall we reveal the correct answer?

95
00:06:55,860 --> 00:06:57,300
The correct answer is...

96
00:06:58,910 --> 00:07:00,210
B.

97
00:07:01,530 --> 00:07:03,560
That makes two.

98
00:07:04,060 --> 00:07:05,130
Amazing.

99
00:07:05,580 --> 00:07:07,120
We’re on a roll.

100
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:09,530
All right, all right.

101
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:12,920
Wow, splendid! Two correct answers in a row.

102
00:07:13,070 --> 00:07:15,590
Maybe they'll manage to stay first-class till the very end.

103
00:07:15,620 --> 00:07:18,060
Check 3: Octet Orchestra

104
00:07:18,140 --> 00:07:20,110
A showdown over their true value.

105
00:07:20,720 --> 00:07:22,890
The correct choice is the most expensive in the show's history.

106
00:07:22,920 --> 00:07:26,900
World-famous instruments worth over 10 billion yen in total.

107
00:07:27,590 --> 00:07:31,940
The real highlight: this is its very first public appearance in Japan.

108
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,290
The Stradivarius 'Corbett'.

109
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:38,940
They'll compare it with a hobby-level instrument.

110
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:41,100
In the main show,

111
00:07:41,120 --> 00:07:44,740
If a musician gets this one wrong,

112
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:45,960
they should really just retire.

113
00:07:45,990 --> 00:07:48,840
Retire?!

114
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:51,360
With their careers on the line in this test,

115
00:07:51,380 --> 00:07:54,810
an incredible six pairs got it wrong.

116
00:07:54,830 --> 00:07:57,480
The few who did get it right...

117
00:07:57,500 --> 00:08:00,420
...burst into tears of joy.

118
00:08:00,450 --> 00:08:04,810
That would mean this is the year Koda Kumi retires.

119
00:08:04,830 --> 00:08:06,690
No, seriously.

120
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:09,030
First, the correct one, A.

121
00:08:09,060 --> 00:08:11,770
The instruments worth over 10 billion yen.

122
00:08:23,660 --> 00:08:28,250
Next, the wrong choice: the hobby-level instrument.

123
00:08:40,960 --> 00:08:43,970
This is rough...

124
00:08:45,190 --> 00:08:47,140
Their answer was...

125
00:08:47,590 --> 00:08:48,960
Split.

126
00:08:48,980 --> 00:08:50,680
Split, huh?

127
00:08:51,560 --> 00:08:53,520
Oh? Why's that?

128
00:08:53,580 --> 00:08:57,710
I went with the classic theory for this one.

129
00:08:57,740 --> 00:08:59,500
'A' felt like it was trying too hard, right?

130
00:08:59,520 --> 00:09:00,780
There it is.
(he says this every time)

131
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:04,730
The high notes sounded really piercing, you know?

132
00:09:04,750 --> 00:09:05,920
Yeah, kind of.

133
00:09:05,940 --> 00:09:08,010
Whereas this one...

134
00:09:08,050 --> 00:09:11,470
...just flowed so naturally.

135
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:14,360
I felt like it played really beautifully.

136
00:09:14,380 --> 00:09:16,920
'A' had a 'hysterical' quality

137
00:09:16,970 --> 00:09:18,860
'Hysterical.'

138
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:20,160
So I chose this one.

139
00:09:20,190 --> 00:09:21,320
How about you?

140
00:09:22,320 --> 00:09:25,540
One decisive thing was the final 'jaaan' chord.

141
00:09:25,590 --> 00:09:28,180
The way it rang out afterwards, this one had more...

142
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:29,060
...you could feel its age.

143
00:09:29,080 --> 00:09:30,790
It just felt more high-end.

144
00:09:30,810 --> 00:09:31,260
Seriously?

145
00:09:31,380 --> 00:09:32,390
At the end?

146
00:09:32,620 --> 00:09:34,280
Wait, really?

147
00:09:34,450 --> 00:09:36,490
(silently switches)

148
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:38,220
Yeah.

149
00:09:38,660 --> 00:09:41,290
Wait.. wait.. wait...

150
00:09:41,350 --> 00:09:43,830
please stop!

151
00:09:45,430 --> 00:09:47,670
Really!?

152
00:09:48,510 --> 00:09:50,030
The correct answer is...

153
00:09:50,060 --> 00:09:51,710
I want to keep top tier

154
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:53,750
A.

155
00:09:54,930 --> 00:09:57,240
So in the end...

156
00:09:58,410 --> 00:10:01,520
For music questions you always say who is doing their best

157
00:10:01,540 --> 00:10:04,660
Please stop this theory

158
00:10:07,170 --> 00:10:11,120
Too bad, Hama-chan, you couldn't stay in the top rank.

159
00:10:11,220 --> 00:10:13,590
Get it right next time, okay?

160
00:10:13,610 --> 00:10:17,480
The fourth test is Michelin-star chefs.

161
00:10:17,510 --> 00:10:22,420
The correct answer is C: Chef Matsumoto of La Paix in Nihonbashi, Tokyo.

162
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:27,300
A top restaurant with one Michelin star for eight years straight.

163
00:10:28,390 --> 00:10:36,470
This time we had Chef Matsumoto make classic Western-style dishes: beef stew and doria.

164
00:10:36,630 --> 00:10:42,010
In the main show, four pairs got it right.

165
00:10:42,240 --> 00:10:46,740
Wrong answer A was a Western-style restaurant in Nippori, Tokyo,

166
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:50,170
run by two brothers, aged 82 and 73:

167
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:53,690
Chefs Tadao Sato and Eiji Sato.

168
00:10:53,710 --> 00:10:58,180
We also had the Sato brothers make both dishes.

169
00:10:58,260 --> 00:11:00,270
Since doria isn't on their menu,

170
00:11:00,360 --> 00:11:03,300
it was their first time making it since they opened.

171
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:08,940
In the main show, three pairs ended up picking the neighborhood restaurant.

172
00:11:08,970 --> 00:11:11,390
ahhh I made a mistake!

173
00:11:12,710 --> 00:11:16,150
And the dreaded two-rank drop,

174
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:21,610
the 'absolutely no good' choice is Chef Hamada, who has fooled 36 people so far.

175
00:11:21,640 --> 00:11:24,620
To be honest, Hamada-san's cooking is

176
00:11:25,020 --> 00:11:28,690
actually really good.

177
00:11:29,030 --> 00:11:31,600
Even GACKT raves about him,

178
00:11:31,620 --> 00:11:35,230
Chef Hamada make beef stew and doria as well.

179
00:11:35,250 --> 00:11:40,870
In the main show, everyone in FRUITS ZIPPER except one member picked Chef Hamada.

180
00:11:40,890 --> 00:11:44,240
These kids are so sweet.

181
00:11:44,260 --> 00:11:48,620
Off they go to the 'Absolutely No Good' room.

182
00:11:49,680 --> 00:11:54,720
This time Hamada will eat the beef stew, and Hirodo-sama will have the doria.

183
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:05,180
First, the wrong answer: the neighborhood restaurant's flavor.

184
00:12:05,200 --> 00:12:07,730
If you refuse we have to stop filming

185
00:12:16,070 --> 00:12:20,720
Next, the two-rank drop: Chef Hamada's dish.

186
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:24,830
You can at least recognize your own cooking, right?

187
00:12:28,650 --> 00:12:31,040
And finally, the correct one:

188
00:12:31,060 --> 00:12:34,620
Chef Matsumoto's dish from La Paix, Nihonbashi.

189
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:43,740
Their answer is...

190
00:12:44,700 --> 00:12:45,450
Ah.

191
00:12:45,670 --> 00:12:47,660
It's pretty amazing to agree when there are three choices.

192
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:50,870
This one was insanely good.

193
00:12:50,890 --> 00:12:53,060
That was the beef stew, right?

194
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:55,320
The tenderness of the meat,

195
00:12:55,560 --> 00:12:59,730
and when you eat it, the slight hint of wine in the sauce...

196
00:12:59,760 --> 00:13:03,480
...just gently wafts up through your nose.

197
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:05,810
It has to be A, no question.

198
00:13:07,200 --> 00:13:08,940
I had the doria,

199
00:13:09,370 --> 00:13:12,760
and A was overwhelmingly creamier.

200
00:13:12,810 --> 00:13:16,800
I think B was probably Hamada-san.

201
00:13:17,580 --> 00:13:18,840
So which one do you think was yours?

202
00:13:18,860 --> 00:13:20,900
The definitely don't pick Hamada-san's cooking?

203
00:13:20,990 --> 00:13:23,300
Which is your beef stew?

204
00:13:24,300 --> 00:13:25,240
C.

205
00:13:27,300 --> 00:13:28,230
Yeah, I figured.

206
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:29,610
Which would mean that, after all...

207
00:13:30,410 --> 00:13:32,360
Then this one is definitely...

208
00:13:32,380 --> 00:13:34,210
If he picked his own...

209
00:13:34,280 --> 00:13:35,700
No way that would happen.

210
00:13:35,720 --> 00:13:36,830
All right, time for the results.

211
00:13:37,380 --> 00:13:39,190
The correct answer is

212
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:40,730
C.

213
00:13:41,500 --> 00:13:42,870
Whoa, hold on.

214
00:13:44,620 --> 00:13:46,960
C was Michelin-starred?

215
00:13:46,980 --> 00:13:48,830
Mine is B.

216
00:13:48,850 --> 00:13:50,480
That's right...

217
00:13:50,570 --> 00:13:52,670
'A' was crazy good.

218
00:13:52,690 --> 00:13:53,680
It was delicious.

219
00:13:53,690 --> 00:13:55,070
 Simple good food

220
00:13:55,100 --> 00:13:56,470
Ah, yes.

221
00:13:57,370 --> 00:13:59,870
Whoa both were wrong.

222
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:04,080
Looks like our dopey-MC era is going strong in 2026 too.

223
00:14:04,100 --> 00:14:07,880
The fifth test is the orchestra.

224
00:14:07,910 --> 00:14:11,740
The correct pro is the Japan Century Symphony Orchestra.

225
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:15,580
One of Japan's leading musicians.

226
00:14:15,600 --> 00:14:18,200
Hisaishi Jo-san fell in love with their performance,

227
00:14:18,230 --> 00:14:21,990
and became their music director in April 2025.

228
00:14:22,760 --> 00:14:26,030
They will be compared with a university orchestra.

229
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:28,450
On vocals, Shigeru Matsuzaki.

230
00:14:28,470 --> 00:14:30,590
Wait, seriously?

231
00:14:30,640 --> 00:14:32,180
He'll be singing 'Ai no Memory'.

232
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:34,270
Of course he is.

233
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:39,450
FRUITS ZIPPER's look-alikes are taking on this round.

234
00:14:39,470 --> 00:14:41,690
If they don't pick the right one, they vanish instantly.

235
00:14:41,700 --> 00:14:43,920
You sure about this?

236
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:48,180
In the end, 1 pair chose A and 6 pairs chose B.

237
00:14:48,240 --> 00:14:53,360
FRUITS ZIPPER are in room B. So, is B the right answer?

238
00:14:57,440 --> 00:14:59,600
A is correct!

239
00:15:00,600 --> 00:15:04,670
FRUITS ZIPPER disappeared with one question still to go.

240
00:15:05,900 --> 00:15:08,090
They've vanished.

241
00:15:08,440 --> 00:15:11,020
By the way, what about this person?

242
00:15:14,440 --> 00:15:16,480
Nicely done, that's correct!

243
00:15:17,340 --> 00:15:21,320
That was really hard.

244
00:15:22,440 --> 00:15:24,460
So what's your musical theory behind that?

245
00:15:24,480 --> 00:15:31,750
The Japan Century Symphony and Kyoto University's symphony orchestra

246
00:15:31,780 --> 00:15:34,540
are both insanely high quality,

247
00:15:34,560 --> 00:15:37,770
so honestly, telling you to judge just from the performance

248
00:15:37,890 --> 00:15:40,020
is pretty tough, in my opinion.

249
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:45,400
But if you flip it and ask instead which one

250
00:15:45,420 --> 00:15:50,470
lets Mr. Matsuzaki really sing the way he wants to,

251
00:15:51,640 --> 00:15:55,300
then once you search for that, it's honestly obvious at a glance,

252
00:15:55,520 --> 00:15:58,000
you can tell right away.

253
00:15:58,020 --> 00:16:01,740
Can Hamada and Hiroto pick the correct one?

254
00:16:01,820 --> 00:16:04,330
First, here is the correct one.

255
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:08,090
♫Beautiful life♫

256
00:16:08,220 --> 00:16:11,120
♫Endless joy♫

257
00:16:11,340 --> 00:16:14,300
♫I give this beating of my heart♫

258
00:16:14,390 --> 00:16:17,490
♫To you♫

259
00:16:17,690 --> 00:16:20,480
Next, the incorrect B version.

260
00:16:20,780 --> 00:16:24,080
♫Even on the day I turn into a star♫

261
00:16:24,400 --> 00:16:28,220
♫I will never part from you.♫

262
00:16:29,930 --> 00:16:33,660
Shigeru, Akira, you're in the way!

263
00:16:33,880 --> 00:16:35,890
Their answer is...

264
00:16:39,140 --> 00:16:42,160
